  "Idea": "This paper proposes a novel framework for enhancing natural language understanding in low-resource languages by integrating subfamily-specific pretraining with custom, linguistically grounded tokenizers derived from shared evolutionary descent. While recent advances have explored data selection based on language relatedness, none have systematically investigated how tokenizer design—a critical determinant of model efficiency and representational capacity—can be optimized using linguistic genealogy. We argue that generic multilingual tokenizers (e.g., SentencePiece in XLM-R) suffer from excessive subword splits in morphologically complex low-resource languages due to vocabulary dilution across unrelated language families. Our solution involves constructing custom Byte-Pair Encoding (BPE) or Unigram tokenizers trained solely on monolingual corpora from languages within a specific subfamily (e.g., Indo-Iranian, Algonquian, or Austronesian). These tokenizers preserve sublexical regularities—such as affixation patterns, reduplication, or tonal marking—that are evolutionarily conserved within language groups. Subsequently, Transformer-based models are pretrained from scratch on the same subfamily corpus using these tailored tokenizers, enabling deeper semantic coherence and parameter-efficient learning. Crucially, we introduce a 'Phylogenetic Tokenizer Optimization' (PTO) algorithm that balances token coverage, merge efficiency, and cross-lingual consistency within the subfamily via a weighted objective combining frequency, cognate alignment, and morphological entropy. We evaluate our approach across 12 typologically diverse subfamilies, measuring performance gains in masked language modeling perplexity, downstream task accuracy (NER, POS tagging, dependency parsing), and zero-shot transfer to unseen sister languages. We further analyze ablation effects by comparing against: (1) multilingual tokenizers, (2) pan-family tokenizers (e.g., all Niger-Congo), and (3)